      {
        "id": 2295643,
        "name": "john stimson",
        "username": "john_stimson",
        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/j/3d9bf3/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2017-11-11T21:25:36.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>We decided to check in on 2005 Red Burg last night.  Wines were all double decanted 4-5 hours before the tasting started.  Most all wines that were healthy were ready to enjoy, but all were still quite primary.  (One of our members who is a Barolo/Barbaresco lover was lamenting that red burgs take so long to evolve from the primary stage\u2013pointing out that by 10-12 years of age, his beloved nebbiolos would already be showing some secondary characteristics.)  A couple of the wines were a little reductive (although subtly so\u2013don\u2019t be afraid to pull out the copper if the wine is seeming a little awkward).  Overall these are stellar, full, engaging wines that for the most part don\u2019t show signs of prolonged shut-down phases, as some had predicted, and should be extremely enjoyable for years.<br>\n<br>\n<br>\nBouchard Volnay \u2018Caillerets Ancienne Cuvee Carnot\u2019\u2013Nicely balanced and sweet, a little bitterness and slight char which at first I thought might be oak, but cleaned up beautifully with a penny, leaving a ripe raspberry-like fruit.  A good showing.</p>\n<p>Henri Boillot Volnay \u2018Les Chevrets\u2019\u2013A little more serious, a bit more oak sweetness, but still quite nice Volnay perfume.  Nicely balanced.  OK now but I\u2019d give it 3 or more years.</p>\n<p>Comte Armand Pommard \u2018Clos des Epeneaux\u2019 Monopole\u2013Rich, dark, beautiful fruit, concentrated but not heavy.  Note of licorice.  Big wine but balanced.  A stud that will be great for years.</p>\n<p>Camus-Brouchon Savigny-les-Beaune \u2018Lavieres\u2019\u2013More high toned red fruits and cranberry, nicely structured and balanced, but leaner after the above wines.  A bit of Savigny earthiness.</p>\n<p>Robert Chevillon Nuits-St-Georges \u2018Les Cailles\u2019\u2013Corked.</p>\n<p>l\u2019Arlot Vosne-Romanee 'les Suchots\u2013lighter in color, lighter weight wine that is beautifully balanced, perfumed cherry and berry fruit.  a little spice, but not as much as many other Vosnes.  A slight hole in the middle, but overall a pleasure.</p>\n<p>Pacalet Chambolle-Musigny premier cru\u2013Nose is almost totally absent other than a little soy.  Palate is slightly stripped.<br>\nNot a whiff of TCA, but other wise seems like one of those phantom corked bottles.  Flawed.</p>\n<p>Lignier-Michelot Morey-St-Denis \u2018Faconnieres\u2019\u2013Beautiful plum, mulberry nose, rich and inviting on the palate, some spice.  Really a joy right now.  (Morey premier crus are under-appreciated in my mind)</p>\n<p>Alain Burguet Gevrey-Chambertin \u2018Mes Favorites\u2019 VV\u2013Deep ripe cherry, berry fruit and generous palate.  The Gevrey fruit here really does almost blast out of the glass.  Not the ultimate in complexity or refinement, but this is generally a bargain.</p>\n<p>Taupenot-Merme Gevrey-Cahmbertin \u2018Bel Air\u2019\u2013Initial high toned tomato note, so I threw another penny in\u2013The tomato disappears and becomes high toned pie cherry.  Engaging wine operating in higher tones than the average Gevrey.</p>",
